Use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` with compiler directives to hook platform-native callbacks:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnPause(activity => {
            // App losing focus / partially hidden
        })
        .OnStop(activity => {
            // App fully backgrounded
        }));
#elif IOS || MACCATALYST
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .DidEnterBackground(app => {
            // App moved to background
        }));
#endif
});
```

**Key mapping:** Android `OnPause` → MAUI `Deactivated`, Android `OnStop` / iOS `DidEnterBackground` → MAUI `Stopped`.

### Cross-platform alternative

If you don't need the native arguments, you can use the **Window `Stopped` event** instead — it maps to `OnStop` on Android and `DidEnterBackground` on iOS automatically:

```csharp
// In App.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* runs on both platforms */ };
    return window;
}
```

**Watch out:** On Android, the back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`, so save critical state in both handlers. Also keep handlers fast (<2 seconds) to avoid ANR/watchdog kills.
